<dxe:ComboBoxEdit x:Name="myCombo"
                  ItemsSource="{Binding YourDataList}"
                  EditValue="{Binding SelectedItems, Mode=TwoWay}"
                  ValidateOnTextInput="True"
                  IncrementalFiltering="True">
    
    <dxe:ComboBoxEdit.StyleSettings>
        <dxe:CheckedComboBoxStyleSettings />
    </dxe:ComboBoxEdit.StyleSettings>

    <dxmvvm:Interaction.Behaviors>
        <dxmvvm:EventToCommand EventName="EditValueChanging" 
                               Command="{Binding LimitSelectionCommand}" 
                               PassEventArgsToCommand="True"/>
    </dxmvvm:Interaction.Behaviors>
</dxe:ComboBoxEdit>


  // In your ViewModel
public void LimitSelectionCommand(EditValueChangingEventArgs e) {
    var newValue = e.NewValue as List<object>;
    
    // If the user tries to select more than 2, stop them
    if (newValue != null && newValue.Count > 2) {
        e.IsCancel = true;
        e.Handled = true;
        
        // Optional: Show a quick message
        // ThemedMessageBox.Show("You can only select up to 2 items.");
    }
DevExpress ComboBoxEdit stores multiple selections as a List<object> in the EditValue. To get your @"{item1}:{item2}" format, you can process it in the setter of your property:

C#
private List<object> _selectedItems;
public List<object> SelectedItems {
    get => _selectedItems;
    set {
        _selectedItems = value;
        OnPropertyChanged();

        // Format the string for your data.item
        if (_selectedItems != null && _selectedItems.Count > 0) {
            // This joins the list into "Item1:Item2"
            string formattedData = string.Join(":", _selectedItems);
            
            // Assign to your target object
            myData.Item = formattedData;
        }
    }
}
Why use EditValueChanging?
If you simply use a standard SelectionChanged event, the third item is added and then removed, which causes a "flicker" in the UI. By using EditValueChanging and setting e.IsCancel = true, the checkbox never actually gets checked, providing a much smoother user experience.

Alternative: Token Mode
If you want it to look like modern tags (like Outlook or Gmail), you can use TokenComboBoxStyleSettings instead of CheckedComboBoxStyleSettings. It works with the same logic but looks more like modern "pills" inside the text box.

  
